(43, 10, 19, 43, 9, 16, 16, NULL, 'Division Among the Jews', 'Both passages emphasize a division among the Jews regarding Jesus'' actions and identity. In John 9:16, the division arises from differing opinions about Jesus'' observance of the Sabbath, while John 10:19 highlights a similar division based on His teachings.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 19, 46, 3, 3, 3, 'division therefore again among the Jews', 'Division Among Believers', 'This connection highlights the theme of division present in both passages. John 10:19 notes a division among the Jews, while 1 Corinthians 3:3 addresses divisions among believers, suggesting a common struggle with discord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 19, 43, 7, 40, 43, NULL, 'Division Among the People', 'Both passages emphasize the division among the people regarding Jesus'' identity. In John 10:19, the division arises from his sayings, while in John 7:40-43, differing opinions about him lead to a similar division.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 19, 44, 14, 4, 4, 'a division therefore again among the Jews', 'Division Among the People', 'This connection highlights the theme of division among groups in response to differing beliefs. Both passages emphasize how factions arise, with some aligning with the Jews and others with the apostles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 19, 44, 23, 7, 10, 'division therefore again among the Jews', 'Division Among the Jews', 'Both passages emphasize division among the Jews, with John 10:19 noting a division due to Jesus'' sayings and Acts 23:7-10 describing a dissension between Pharisees and Sadducees. This connection highlights the ongoing conflict and differing beliefs within the Jewish community.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 19, 40, 10, 34, 35, 'division therefore again among the Jews', 'Division and Conflict Themes', 'Both passages emphasize division and conflict arising from Jesus'' teachings. John 10:19 notes a division among the Jews, while Matthew 10:34-35 speaks of setting family members against each other, highlighting the disruptive nature of His message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 19, 42, 12, 51, 53, 'division', 'Division Among Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of division resulting from Jesus'' teachings. In John, the division among the Jews reflects the contentious response to His words, while in Luke, Jesus explicitly states that His coming will bring division within families.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 20, 43, 7, 20, 20, NULL, 'Accusations of Madness', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation of having a devil, reflecting the people''s skepticism towards Jesus. This connection highlights the theme of misunderstanding and rejection faced by Jesus during His ministry.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 20, 41, 3, 21, 21, NULL, 'Perception of Jesus'' Mental State', 'Both passages emphasize the perception of Jesus as being ''beside himself'' or ''mad.'' This connection highlights how those around Him questioned His sanity.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 20, 43, 8, 47, 48, NULL, 'Accusations of Madness and Devil', 'Both passages emphasize accusations against Jesus, labeling him as having a devil. This connection highlights the rejection of his divine authority by those who do not hear God''s words.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 20, 23, 53, 8, 8, 'why hear ye him?', 'Rejection of the Suffering Servant', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection present in both passages. In John 10:20, the people question Jesus'' sanity, paralleling the idea in Isaiah 53:8 of being cut off and unrecognized.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 20, 40, 9, 34, 34, 'he hath a devil', 'Accusations of Madness and Demons', 'Both passages emphasize accusations against Jesus regarding demonic influence. In John 10:20, he is called ''mad'' and possessed by a devil, while in Matthew 9:34, the Pharisees claim he casts out devils through the prince of devils.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 20, 40, 10, 25, 25, 'he hath a devil, and is mad', 'Accusations Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being called mad or possessed. In John 10:20, Jesus is accused of having a devil, while Matthew 10:25 reflects that His disciples will face similar accusations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 20, 44, 18, 14, 15, 'He hath a devil, and is mad', 'Rejection of Divine Messengers', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by those proclaiming God''s message. In both passages, individuals question the sanity or legitimacy of the speaker, reflecting a broader pattern of skepticism towards divine authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 21, 2, 4, 11, 11, 'open the eyes of the blind', 'Connection of Blindness and Healing', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority over sight and blindness. Both passages emphasize God''s power to open the eyes of the blind, suggesting a link between miraculous healing and divine identity.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 21, 19, 94, 9, 9, 'open the eyes of the blind', 'Connection of Sight and Hearing', 'Both passages emphasize the ability to see and hear, questioning the capacity of God to perceive what He has created. John 10:21 refers to the opening of the eyes of the blind, while Psalms 94:9 speaks of the one who formed the eye and ear. This connection highlights the theme of divine perception and capability.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 21, 23, 35, 5, 6, 'open the eyes of the blind', 'Healing and Restoration Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the opening of the eyes of the blind, highlighting a theme of healing and restoration. John 10:21 references the ability to open the eyes of the blind, which aligns with Isaiah 35:5-6''s prophetic vision of such miraculous events.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 21, 40, 11, 5, 5, 'open the eyes of the blind', 'Healing Miracles and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous healing of the blind, highlighting Jesus'' authority and divine power. The question in John 10:21 about a devil opening the eyes of the blind connects directly to the miracles listed in Matthew 11:5.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 21, 2, 8, 19, 19, 'open the eyes of the blind', 'Divine Power Recognition', 'Both passages emphasize recognition of divine power. In John, the ability to open the eyes of the blind suggests a divine act, while in Exodus, the magicians acknowledge the finger of God, indicating a similar recognition of God''s authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 21, 19, 146, 8, 8, 'open the eyes of the blind', 'Opening Eyes of the Blind', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine power in opening the eyes of the blind. Both passages emphasize the miraculous ability to restore sight, suggesting a link between Jesus'' actions and God''s authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 21, 20, 20, 12, 12, 'open the eyes of the blind', 'Connection of Sight and Hearing', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of sight and hearing as divine gifts. John 10:21 highlights the miraculous opening of the eyes, while Proverbs 20:12 states that the Lord made both the seeing eye and hearing ear.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 23, 44, 3, 11, 11, NULL, 'Connection of Solomon''s Porch', 'Both passages emphasize Solomon''s porch as a significant location. In John, Jesus walks there, while in Acts, it serves as the gathering place after a healing.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 23, 44, 5, 12, 12, 'Solomons porch', 'Connection through Solomon''s Porch', 'Both passages emphasize the location of Solomon''s porch, where significant events occur involving Jesus and the apostles. This connection highlights the continuity of divine activity in the same sacred space.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 24, 42, 22, 67, 70, 'If thou be the Christ, tell us plainly', 'Questioning Christ''s Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the questioning of Jesus'' identity as the Christ. In John, the Jews demand a clear answer, while in Luke, the inquiry about being the Christ leads to a profound declaration of his authority.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 24, 43, 1, 19, 19, 'How long dost thou make us to doubt?', 'Inquiry About Identity', 'Both passages emphasize a questioning of identity. In John 10:24, the Jews ask Jesus if he is the Christ, while in John 1:19, they send priests to inquire about Johns identity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 24, 40, 11, 3, 3, 'If thou be the Christ', 'Questioning Jesus'' Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the uncertainty surrounding Jesus'' identity as the Messiah. In John 10:24, the Jews ask if He is the Christ, while in Matthew 11:3, the question is whether He is the one who should come.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 24, 43, 8, 25, 25, 'How long dost thou make us to doubt?', 'Identity and Doubt in Jesus'' Claims', 'Both passages emphasize the questioning of Jesus'' identity. In John 10:24, the Jews ask if he is the Christ, while in John 8:25, they inquire about who he is, highlighting their doubt and confusion regarding his claims.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 24, 11, 18, 21, 21, 'How long dost thou make us to doubt?', 'Doubt and Decision', 'This connection highlights the theme of indecision in both passages. In John, the Jews question Jesus, asking, ''How long dost thou make us to doubt?'' Similarly, Elijah challenges the people, asking, ''How long halt ye between two opinions?''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 24, 42, 3, 15, 15, 'if thou be the Christ', 'Expectation of the Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the questioning of identity regarding the Christ. In John, the Jews ask Jesus directly if he is the Christ, while in Luke, the people ponder whether John is the Christ.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 24, 47, 3, 12, 12, 'tell us plainly', 'Plainness of Speech', 'This connection highlights the theme of clarity in communication. In John 10:24, the Jews ask for a plain declaration of Christ''s identity, while 2 Corinthians 3:12 emphasizes using great plainness of speech in conveying hope.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
