VALUES
(43, 10, 34, 2, 4, 16, 16, 'Ye are gods', 'Divine Authority and Representation', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority where humans are depicted as representatives of God. In John 10:34, the phrase ''Ye are gods'' suggests a shared authority, while Exodus 4:16 indicates that Moses will act as God to Aaron, emphasizing the role of humans as mediators of divine will.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 34, 19, 138, 1, 1, 'Ye are gods', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''gods'' in both passages. In John 10:34, Jesus references the idea of humans being called ''gods,'' while Psalms 138:1 mentions singing praise before the ''gods.''', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 34, 43, 8, 17, 17, NULL, 'Connection of Legal Testimony', 'Both passages emphasize legal principles found in the law. John 10:34 references the authority of God''s word, while John 8:17 discusses the validity of testimony, highlighting the importance of law in establishing truth.', 'theme', 0.272, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 34, 43, 12, 34, 34, 'Ye are gods', 'Connection of Law and Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the law and its implications for identity. In John 10:34, Jesus references the law to assert a divine identity, while in John 12:34, the people refer to the law regarding the eternal nature of Christ, questioning his identity as the Son of man.', 'theme', 0.272, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 34, 45, 3, 10, 19, 'Ye are gods', 'Righteousness and Human Nature', 'Both passages emphasize the flawed nature of humanity. John 10:34 highlights the divine potential in humans, while Romans 3:10-19 underscores their unrighteousness and lack of understanding.', 'theme', 0.258, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 35, 40, 24, 35, 35, 'the scripture cannot be broken', 'Enduring Nature of God''s Word', 'Both passages emphasize the permanence of God''s word. John 10:35 states that ''the scripture cannot be broken,'' while Matthew 24:35 asserts that ''my words shall not pass away.''', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 35, 45, 13, 1, 1, NULL, 'Authority and Divine Ordination', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority as both passages discuss the nature of power and its divine origin. John 10:35 emphasizes that scripture cannot be broken, affirming the authority of God''s word, while Romans 13:1 states that all powers are ordained of God, linking human authority to divine will.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 35, 42, 16, 17, 17, 'the scripture cannot be broken', 'Authority of Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the unbreakable nature of scripture and the law. John 10:35 asserts that ''the scripture cannot be broken,'' while Luke 16:17 highlights that ''one tittle of the law to fail'' is impossible.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 35, 42, 24, 44, 46, 'the scripture cannot be broken', 'Fulfillment of Scripture', 'This connection highlights the authority of scripture in both passages. John emphasizes that ''the scripture cannot be broken,'' while Luke discusses how all things must be fulfilled that were written in the scriptures concerning Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 35, 1, 15, 1, 1, 'the word of God came', 'Connection of God''s Word', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the word of God coming to individuals. In John 10:35, it highlights that the scripture cannot be broken, while Genesis 15:1 shows the word of the Lord coming to Abram, affirming its authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 35, 44, 1, 16, 16, 'the scripture cannot be broken', 'Fulfillment of Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of scripture. John 10:35 asserts that ''the scripture cannot be broken,'' while Acts 1:16 highlights that ''this scripture must needs have been fulfilled.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 35, 5, 18, 15, 15, 'the word of God came', 'Connection of Prophetic Authority', 'This connection highlights the authority of those who receive the word of God. Both passages emphasize the role of divinely appointed figures, with John referencing those called ''gods'' and Deuteronomy speaking of a Prophet to whom people should listen.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 36, 43, 3, 17, 17, 'sent into the world', 'Connection of Divine Sending', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God sending His Son into the world. John 10:36 highlights Jesus'' divine sanctification and mission, while John 3:17 clarifies that this mission is for salvation, not condemnation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 36, 43, 5, 17, 18, 'I am the Son of God', 'Jesus'' Divine Sonship', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' claim of being the Son of God, which leads to conflict with the Jewish leaders. In John 10:36, Jesus defends his identity, while in John 5:18, his assertion of God as his Father is seen as making himself equal with God.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 36, 24, 1, 5, 5, 'sanctified', 'Sanctification and Divine Knowledge', 'This connection highlights the theme of sanctification, as both passages mention being sanctified by God. John 10:36 refers to Jesus being sanctified and sent, while Jeremiah 1:5 speaks of being sanctified before birth, emphasizing God''s divine purpose.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 36, 19, 2, 2, 2, 'I am the Son of God', 'Connection of Divine Sonship', 'Both passages emphasize the opposition faced by God''s chosen. John 10:36 refers to Jesus as the ''Son of God,'' while Psalms 2:2 speaks of rulers conspiring against ''his anointed.'' This connection highlights the theme of rejection of God''s appointed leaders.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 36, 23, 61, 1, 3, 'whom the Father hath sanctified, and sent', 'Connection of Anointing and Sonship', 'This connection highlights the theme of being sent and anointed. Both passages emphasize the role of the one sent by God to bring healing and liberation, linking Jesus'' identity as the ''Son of God'' with the anointed mission described in Isaiah.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 36, 40, 27, 43, 43, 'I am the Son of God', 'Connection of Sonship Claims', 'Both passages emphasize the claim of being ''the Son of God.'' In John 10:36, Jesus defends his identity against accusations, while Matthew 27:43 presents mockery of that same claim during his crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 36, 42, 1, 35, 35, 'I am the Son of God', 'Connection of Sonship', 'This connection highlights the concept of Jesus as the ''Son of God'' in both passages. John 10:36 refers to Jesus as the Son of God, while Luke 1:35 describes the divine origin of Jesus as the Son of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 37, 43, 15, 24, 24, 'the works of my Father', 'Connection of Works and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of ''works'' as a demonstration of divine authority. In John 10:37, Jesus challenges belief based on His works, while in John 15:24, He refers to His unique works as evidence against those who reject Him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 37, 43, 10, 25, 25, 'the works of my Father', 'Connection of Jesus'' Works', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of Jesus'' works as evidence of his divine authority. In John 10:25, Jesus states that the works he does in his Fathers name bear witness of him, while in John 10:37, he challenges the listeners to believe based on those same works.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 37, 40, 11, 20, 24, 'the works of my Father', 'Connection of Mighty Works', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of mighty works as evidence of divine authority. John 10:37 challenges belief based on works, while Matthew 11:20-24 condemns cities for not repenting despite witnessing those works.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 37, 43, 5, 31, 31, 'the works of my Father', 'Connection of Witness and Works', 'Both passages emphasize the validity of testimony through actions. John 10:37 refers to the works of the Father as a basis for belief, while John 5:31 suggests that self-witness lacks credibility without corroborating evidence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 37, 43, 12, 37, 40, 'the works of my Father', 'Connection of Belief and Works', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between belief and the works of Jesus. In John 10:37, Jesus challenges the audience to believe based on His works, while John 12:37-40 illustrates the failure to believe despite witnessing many miracles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 38, 43, 14, 20, 20, NULL, 'Unity with the Father', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between Jesus and the Father, highlighting the mutual indwelling. The phrase ''I am in my Father'' connects the two verses, illustrating a theme of divine unity.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 38, 43, 10, 25, 25, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Works', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' works as evidence of his divine authority. In John 10:25, Jesus states that his works bear witness of him, while in John 10:38, he invites belief in his works to understand his unity with the Father.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 38, 43, 3, 2, 2, NULL, 'Connection of Miraculous Works', 'Both passages emphasize the connection between Jesus'' miracles and his divine authority. John 10:38 invites belief in Jesus'' works to recognize the unity with the Father, while John 3:2 acknowledges that no one can perform such miracles without God''s presence.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 38, 43, 17, 21, 23, 'that the Father is in me, and I in him', 'Unity in Christ and the Father', 'Both passages emphasize the unity between Jesus and the Father, as well as the call for believers to share in that unity. The phrase ''I in them, and thou in me'' in the target passage echoes the relationship described in the source verse, highlighting the interconnectedness of their faith.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 38, 44, 2, 22, 22, 'believe the works', 'Connection of Divine Approval', 'Both passages emphasize the validation of Jesus'' ministry through miraculous works. John highlights belief in Jesus'' works as evidence of divine presence, while Acts refers to Jesus being ''approved of God'' through miracles and signs.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 38, 44, 4, 8, 12, 'believe the works', 'Connection of Works and Salvation', 'This connection highlights the emphasis on belief in the works of Jesus as a means to recognize His divine authority. Both passages affirm that healing and salvation come through Jesus, underscoring the significance of His actions as evidence of His relationship with the Father.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
